Because power dislikes being democratized, documented experiences of liquid democracies are few but offer insights on how to improve its dynamics on future iterations. We took the lessons learned from them to help define key aspects of the user experience provided by Sovereign.

====2.4.1 Liquid.====

[http://www.tdcommons.org/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1092&context=dpubs_series Google Votes] was an internal implementation made for Google employees led by engineer Steve Hardt. He created a liquid democracy plug-in to be used on the internal network of Google+ and tested different ballot and tallying methods. With 15,000 participants, 371 decisions were made on a wide range of issues that went from choosing office snacks to deciding the lunch menu. The key finding from this research was the lack of delegations: only 3.6% of votes were delegated making the system a direct democracy for the most part. Delegations happened mostly among those users who actively campaigned to attract them.

