We believe that it is key to provide a user experience that makes the delegation interaction immediate and simple reducing any kind of friction in the process. The delegation widget must be constantly exposed on the interface while browsing issues or looking at member profiles. For this purpose, Sovereign uses a ''liquid bar'' that is able to effectively communicate to the user his available ''VOTEs'' to cast for any decision or delegation. We see this interaction as a step forward from the ''like'' pattern found in social media limiting voting interactinos to a single click or tap.

====2.4.2 Delegations.====

When the German Pirate Party implemented [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LiquidFeedback Liquid Feedback], a pioneering liquid democracy software developed in 2009, it reached a participation level of ~550 affiliates that led to [http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/liquid-democracy-web-platform-makes-professor-most-powerful-pirate-a-818683.html a linguist professor becoming the most influential member of the party]. Martin Haase was in charge of translating all uploaded propositions in the system to a neutral language in order to avoid any ideological bias, making him grasp 167 delegations from other members. The consequences of having a monopolizing leader in a liquid democracy environment goes against the spirit of an ecosystem that aims to incentivize more participation. Also, a potential scenario that can unfold with a widespread liquid democracy is having ''celebrities'' or well known members suddenly being able to attract most of the delegated votes. An attacker willing to subvert a liquid democracy can promote a superstar on television wearing a QR code to get a sudden influx of delegations in the exposed address from fans and viewers, instantly becoming a monopolizing force.

For this purpose a key setting on a liquid democracy system is to permit [http://ericposner.com/quadratic-voting/ quadratic voting when it comes to delegations]. This means that the cost for Alice to delegate votes to Bob increases exponentially the more votes get delegated. With quadratic voting, Alice can only delegate Bob 1, 2, 4, 8, 16 or even 128 or 512 ''VOTEs'' but no value in between. This makes any delegation transaction tax the delegator by drastically reducing the opportunity cost of delegating to other members. This method prevents the rise of any monopolies or duopolies within the market dynamics of liquid democracies, granting an incentive to participate for every member of an organization. But if any user desires to delegate a significant amount of ''VOTEs'' to another member, it comes with the price of becoming powerless.

